    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so with the ARM, how do i actually know how much it could change? like is there a limit to how much they can hike the rate if the market goes crazy? i'm just worried about it being totally unpredictable.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to be worried about the \"unpredictable\" part of an ARM, because that is exactly what makes them so tricky for first-time buyers! In the world of mortgages, there is a concept called the \"cap,\" which is basically a safety net that limits how much the rate can jump up or down.\n\nThink of the cap as a guardrail on a steep hill. If the market goes crazy and interest rates skyrocket, the ARM won't let your payment go up forever; it will hit a ceiling, usually set by the lender. For example, a common cap might be 5% or 6% per year. So, even if the market is in a frenzy, your monthly payment can only increase by that specific percentage before the lender gets tired of it.\n\nHowever, there is also a \"floor\" to consider, which is the minimum rate the lender will allow you to pay, usually tied to the prime rate. So, while you can't go *too* high, you also can't go *too* low. This means your payment is bounded, but it still has a range of movement.\n\nTo give you a concrete idea of the \"how much,\" let's say your current ARM",
      "source": "target",
